post_text:
It has been wonderful to see so many of our Alpine Union School District families grabbing breakfast and lunch to go the past two weeks!!

We will be serving Breakfast and Lunch To Go Bags every Monday (or the first school day of the week if there is a holiday) during Distant Learning from 11 am to 12 pm. All To Go Bags will have 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches, one bag per student. Your student has to be enrolled in one of our Alpine Union School District schools to participate in this program.

Please fill out a Free and Reduced Meal Waiver with the link below to see if you qualify for this amazing assistance program:
https://www.alpineschools.net/o/ausd/page/free-and-reduced-meal-program--2

Cost per student for 5 days:
Free: $0
Reduced: $3.50
Full Pay: $26.35

If you have any questions or need assistance, please call our Child Nutrition Services Director Kelly Massey at (619) 445-3639 or email at kmassey@alpineschools.net.

Creekside Early Learning Center
July 31 at 2:45 PM ·

Good morning future, current and former Cubs. It is time to launch the 2020-21 “Cubs in the Community” campaign. Connecting with kids is one of the most essential part of building relationships and fostering learning. Mrs. Ripke has set a goal to connect with 100 future, current, and former Cubs in the community by the 100th day of school. If you spot Mrs. Ripke out in the community, please say hi and take a picture with her. Former CELC staff count too! Our pictures may look different this year due to social distancing; however, all of the love will still be there! She can’t wait to hand out hugs again when it is safe. Here is our first Cub of the year!

Dear AUSD Families,
We realize that everyone is eager for answers as to what school routines will look like when the new school year begins. With this in mind, we have designed the AUSD Safe Schools Parent And Student Reopening Guidebook. It provides a road map for how our schools will operate in the 2020-21 school year. The guidebook along with all communications and updates are posted on our COVID-19 page on our website. The Guidebook, our Reopening Plan, and the list of Frequently Asked Questions and other resources are located on the page. Here is the link to the Guidebook. https://core-docs.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/asset/uploaded_file/819514/2020-21_AUSD_SCHOOL_REOPENING_GUIDEBOOK.pdf

post_text:
AUSD 2020-21 Registration Extended Until Friday, July 31

We are extending the 2020-21 Student Learning Model Registration until Friday, July 31 at 4:00 PM. While we will be beginning the year with distance learning, we plan to transition to face-to-face learning when health conditions allow. It is imperative that each child is registered for the learning model of your choice by Friday, July 31 so that we are able to staff appropriately. If a registration form is not completed for each child we may not be able to place your child in the learning mode of your choice when we reopen our campuses. Please check our COVID-19 webpage for a list of frequently asked questions. This page is updated daily with all communications and key information. The 2020-21 Student Learning Model Registration registration form can be found at the following link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/PSV68FS

post_text:
We are continuing our plans to reopen schools on August 19. To ensure that your child is placed in the learning model of your choice and we are able to staff appropriately, the 2020-21 Student Learning Model Registration form is required to be filled out for each student. The registration period will be open until July 27, 2020. If a registration form is not completed for each child we will not be able to place your child in a learning model.

Parents registering for a learning model will have the flexibility of changing models. We will provide a window at the end of September for families to reassess their learning model choice for their children.

To complete the 2020-21 Student Learning Model Registration form please access the link below.
https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/PSV68FS

post_text:
IMPORTANT NOTICE: You might be eligible to get $365 per child to help feed your family, in addition to any grab-n-go meals you may be getting. Because schools are closed due to COVID-19, families who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals can get extra food benefits to help feed their children. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on a P-EBT card. You can use your P-EBT card like a debit card to buy food and groceries for your children.

Most families who receive CalFresh, CalWORKS, Medi-Cal, or other social services benefits will get a P-EBT card in the mail before May 22. Please keep an eye out for this card in the mail over the next few weeks.

Other families will need to complete a simple and quick online application before June 30, 2020.

For more information, visit ca.p-ebt.org/info

Pizza Day!
Grab and go meals for students are available for pick up at Boulder Oaks Elementary School between 11-12 today and tomorrow. We ask that you pull in, remain in your car and, if possible, open your trunk or hatch so our staff can place the lunches in your vehicle and keep a social distance. Beginning next Monday, March 30, we will provide a week of meals for pick up on Mondays only. Please help spread the word. Grab and go meals are open for any student age 18 and under and open to neighboring districts as well.

Lastly, we will continue to check out Chromebooks to students who need one during this time. #Alpine #AUSD #UNITED #Alpinestrong #onwardandupward

post_text:
Although there are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Alpine Union, out of an abundance of caution, and in consultation with the California Public Health Officials, Alpine Union School District will close all schools in a statewide effort to prevent the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19).

School will remain open today with normal dismissal procedures. Schools will be closed beginning Monday, March 16th with plans to reopen beginning Tuesday, April 14th.

Our District and school leaders have been preparing for potential school closures. We will be following up with more information including educational resources we will make available to our families and students.

Although there are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Alpine Union, out of an abundance of caution, and in consultation with the California Public Health Officials, Alpine Union School District will close all schools in a statewide effort to prevent the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19).

School will remain open today with normal dismissal procedures. Schools will be closed beginning Monday, March 16th with plans to reopen beginning Tuesday, April 14th.

Our District and school leaders have been preparing for potential school closures. We will be following up with more information including educational resources we will make available to our families and students.

post_text: How do you connect science, literature and critical thinking? Well, ask a Creekside cub! After reading many versions of The Gingerbread Man, students designed boats so the gingerbread cookie could safely cross the river and not have to hitch a ride on the fox's back. Students were challenged to make a boat that could stay afloat for 5 minutes and keep the cookie dry. Successful designers were rewarded with a crispy cookie to eat, and unsuccessful boats ended with a soggy cookie and a trip back to the drawing board. #scienceisfun #kindergarten #onwardandupward #AUSD #Alpine #criticalthinkers

post_text:
At the Alpine Union School District, our top priority is to provide a safe and secure learning environment for our students.

You have probably heard about the increased risk of wildfire and potential power outages this week, and I want to make sure to keep the school community well informed.

We met with Alpine Fire Marshall Jason McBroom today to discuss fire protocols, safety, and potential SDGE safety-related power outages, which are possible Thursday or Friday.

We will continue to coordinate with local responders in the event of weather-related warnings. These warnings do not automatically mean we will cancel school. However, to ensure student safety, we may decide to cancel classes based on the circumstances and guidance from the local fire department. If there is a power outage, we may cancel school, depending on the duration.

We will be sure to stay in touch with updates as they become available.

SDG&E provides up-to-date information on which areas may be impacted by power outages. Click here to access the site.

Our sixth graders loved playing the role of archeologist while studying ancient civilizations! Of course, they used tools to excavate chocolate chips from cookies (without damaging them) instead of bones and ancient artifacts. Their sweet treat artifacts were even cleaned up and mapped, just like a hands on archeologist would have done!

#AUSD #Alpine #onwardandupward #keepmovingforward #grantwinner #futuregeneration #kindness #positiveclimate #education #californiaeducation #futurearcheologists #history #ancientcivilization

post_text: On behalf of Hannah’s family, we respectfully share the following message: The fundraiser is this Saturday from 5 to 8 (see flyer). Tickets for adults are $25 and $10 for children, which includes a Mexican dinner. There will be activities including a pie in your face station, face painting, an interactive jumper for the kids, a slime making station, popcorn, snow cones, cotton candy, and a bake sale with all proceeds going to Hannah. There will be a raffle including items such as bikes, gift baskets, a PS4, and other items. There will also be a silent raffle. The Sheriff’s canine unit will be giving kids badges. The fire department will be joining us, along with the police helicopter. T-shirts will be available including golden ribbons that stand for childhood cancer. We are hoping Hannah is well enough to join for the fundraiser. All monies to be donated can go to East Valley Christian fellowship. In the memo portion please put: For Hannah Grace. We appreciate all the help, and your prayers are coveted. If you have any questions, please contact Toni Brinegar 619-546-3968

post_text:
Early this year, we joined forces with 10 other small school districts and the SDCOE to submit a federal grant to enhance our social and emotional support for students. We are thrilled to share that the grant was funded at $3,750,0000. Alpine Union will be one of the leads on the grant and will receive $535,000 for this project over five years. We can’t wait to see the positive impact this grant makes on our schools and especially our students. This year we hired a social worker to support our students and staff and this will only enhance the work we are undertaking.

#AUSD #Alpine #onwardandupward #keepmovingforward #grantwinner #futuregeneration #kindness #positiveclimate #education #californiaeducation

We hope all of our families are enjoying the summer break. It is time to register students who will be riding the bus during the 2019-20 school year. All students MUST complete the online registration application form and payment process no later than August 7, 2019. Students who do not complete the registration form and payment by the deadline will not be able to ride the bus the first week of school.
To register, simply go to the District website at www.alpineschools.net and click on the Transportation Department tab. Click here to access the site.
If you have any questions feel free to call the Dispatch Office at the Grossmont Union High School District (GUHSD) at 619-644-8186. The GUHSD Dispatch Office is open all year, with the exception of major holidays, from 4:30 am until 5:00 pm, should you have any questions about bus schedules. You may also call the AUSD District Office at 619-445-3236.

post_text: JMMS Engineering students earned another national accolade at the 2019 Jr Solar Sprint in Washington, DC this past week by winning the sprint racing segment of the competition and by finishing 2nd in the overall scoring. The team, comprised of 6th, 7th and 8th graders, traveled to the annual Technology Student Association convention, where they competed against 94 teams from around the nation for top honors. This is the second top-three finish for the program in the past three years.
